<taxonomicName id="B8894D563B60FFFCFF5AFCDEFDC3FCFE" authority="wagneri" authorityName="wagneri (FLACH" authorityYear="2006" box="[227,565,819,846]" class="Insecta" family="Apionidae" genus="Hemitrichapion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="131" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="wagneri" subSpecies="wagneri">
<emphasis id="4DFDEAC73B60FFFCFF5AFCDEFDC3FCFE" box="[227,565,819,846]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="131">Hemitrichapion wagneri wagneri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
vs. 
<emphasis id="4DFDEAC73B60FFFCFDE7FCDEFCFBFCFE" box="[606,781,819,846]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="131">
H. w. 
<taxonomicName id="B8894D563B60FFFCFD22FCDEFCFBFCFE" authorityName="Stuben &amp; Behne" authorityYear="2010" box="[667,781,819,846]" class="Insecta" family="Apionidae" genus="Hemitrichapion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="131" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gomerense">gomerense</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="7F3636D53B60FFFCFF5AFCBEFE40FCDE" blockId="4.[227,781,819,878]" box="[227,438,851,878]" pageId="4" pageNumber="131">– just a colour play?</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="3793655E3B60FFFCFF04FC64FEF9F991" pageId="4" pageNumber="131" type="reference_group">
<paragraph id="7F3636D53B60FFFCFF04FC64FEF9F991" blockId="4.[189,795,905,1569]" pageId="4" pageNumber="131">
<taxonomicName id="B8894D563B60FFFCFF04FC64FF04FC71" authority="STUBEN &amp; BEHNE, 2010" authorityName="STUBEN &amp; BEHNE" authorityYear="2010" class="Insecta" family="Apionidae" genus="Hemitrichapion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="131" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="wagneri" subSpecies="gomerense">
<emphasis id="4DFDEAC73B60FFFCFF04FC64FDCBFC11" box="[189,573,905,929]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="131">Hemitrichapion wagneri gomerense</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="1B184B243B60FFFCFDF3FC67FF04FC71" author="STUBEN, P. E. &amp; BEHNE, L." pageId="4" pageNumber="131" refId="ref6512" refString="STUBEN, P. E. &amp; BEHNE, L. 2010: Hemitrichapion gomerense sp. n. (Coleoptera: Curculionoidea: Apionidae). - WEEVIL NEWS: - http: // www. curci. de / Inhalt &amp; WEEVIL NEWS (printable version) 53 (12 July 2010): 3 pp., CURCULIO-Institute: Monchengladbach. - PDF - (see: &lt;http: // www. curci. de /? beitrag = 162&gt;)." type="book" year="2010">STÜBEN &amp; BEHNE, 2010</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, is without exception a red-copper metallic species on La Gomera (
<typeStatus id="A03288773B60FFFCFED7FC24FE68FC51" box="[366,414,969,993]" pageId="4" pageNumber="131">type</typeStatus>
locality) and El Hierro, while the nominotypic taxon from the Iberian Peninsula appears bluish green (
<typeStatus id="A03288773B60FFFCFEE4FBE4FE7BFB91" box="[349,397,1033,1057]" pageId="4" pageNumber="131">type</typeStatus>
locality is Cascais, 
<collectingCountry id="079E76453B60FFFCFDC1FBE4FD21FB91" box="[632,727,1033,1057]" name="Portugal" pageId="4" pageNumber="131">Portugal</collectingCountry>
). The two subspecies living on various 
<taxonomicName id="B8894D563B60FFFCFD8CFBC7FD33FBF1" box="[565,709,1065,1089]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Lotus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="4" pageNumber="131" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis id="4DFDEAC73B60FFFCFD8CFBC7FD99FBF1" box="[565,623,1066,1089]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="131">Lotus</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
cannot actually be confused with each other and are certainly not conspecific from a morphological point of view! However on Tenerife there even seems to be two species/ subspecies: 
<taxonomicName id="B8894D563B60FFFCFEF9FB47FDD1FB71" authorityName="STUBEN &amp; BEHNE" authorityYear="2010" box="[320,551,1194,1217]" class="Insecta" family="Apionidae" genus="Hemitrichapion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="131" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="wagneri" subSpecies="gomerense">
<emphasis id="4DFDEAC73B60FFFCFEF9FB47FDD1FB71" box="[320,551,1194,1217]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="131">H. wagneri gomerense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and another coppercoloured, cryptic (sub)species, which clusters together with 
<taxonomicName id="B8894D563B60FFFCFF41FB07FD82FAB1" authority="wagneri (FLACH, 2006)" authorityName="wagneri (FLACH" authorityYear="2006" baseAuthorityName="FLACH" baseAuthorityYear="2006" box="[248,628,1257,1281]" class="Insecta" family="Apionidae" genus="Hemitrichapion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="131" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="wagneri" subSpecies="wagneri">
<emphasis id="4DFDEAC73B60FFFCFF41FB07FE3DFAB1" box="[248,459,1258,1281]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="131">H. wagneri wagneri</emphasis>
(FLACH, 2006)
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry id="079E76453B60FFFCFD06FB04FCECFAB1" box="[703,794,1257,1281]" name="Portugal" pageId="4" pageNumber="131">Portugal</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingRegion id="BD4DF8373B60FFFCFF7DFAE4FEA7FA91" box="[196,337,1289,1313]" country="Spain" name="Extremadura" pageId="4" pageNumber="131">Estremadura</collectingRegion>
) and 
<collectingCountry id="079E76453B60FFFCFE2BFAE4FE38FA91" box="[402,462,1289,1313]" name="Spain" pageId="4" pageNumber="131">Spain</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingRegion id="BD4DF8373B60FFFCFE64FAE4FDB9FA91" box="[477,591,1289,1313]" country="Spain" name="Andalucia" pageId="4" pageNumber="131">Andalucía</collectingRegion>
) in the tree. If the clear clade formation can be confirmed, there would be no objection to a (sub)species splitting, but in such cases one should not forego the molecular investigation of many more populations from the named islands in order to exclude polyphyly and/or paraphyly; otherwise - and in what we consider to be a very unlikely case - the two (sub)species would only be colour variants of the same species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
